text: My dad is Brad Strickland, who continued the Bellairs series after John Bellairs passed away. The film producers were kind enough to invite my family to the set to see the production in progress. I was absolutely astounded by the detail -- I've been on film sets before and usually when you get up close everything looks really fake. This one didn't. It was clear the set design, props and costume departments had all gone to incredible lengths to make the film look special. I got to see a really cool scene being shot (there's a tiny glimpse of it in this trailer). Obviously that was before any effects or processing could be done to the movie. This trailer looks fantastic. I love the tone. I can't wait to see the movie!

The kid's uncle turns out to be a wizard; HP turns out to be a wizard. The uncle & the witch who's his best friend are the template for Dumbledore & McGonagall. text: This is super late, but I don't care. I am very disappointed by this. I loved Bellairs' books as a kid. Hell, I still do. His novels were eerie, gothic fare illustrated by the inimitable Edward Gorey. Yes they were geared to youth/young adult and so weren't full of sex, swearing and gratuitous gore, but they *were* 100% dark, gothic horror/mystery; very much in the vein of M. R. James. Of course no movie is exactly like its source (and that's fine) but this bright, colorful art direction and cheap childish "humor" is literally the *antithesis* of the original book and its art style! It's way past due for any Bellairs novel to hit the big screen, but I can't help but be disappointed that they sucked the very soul out of his work and made it into this silly, campy, cartoony crap instead. It's lost all the creepy atmosphere and style that was so much a part of what made it great. Sigh. Maybe someday someone will remake/reboot this properly. We can only hope.
